Every [`PSPDFAnnotation`][] in a document can specify flags that further define its behavior and capabilities. With PSPDFKit, you can access these flags directly on your annotation objects using the [`flags`][] property.

## Capabilities of Flags

Annotation flags are part of the PDF specification and define an annotationâ€™s behavior, its presentation onscreen and on paper, and the available editing features given to your users. Here are a few examples of things you can do with flags:

- An annotation with a [`PSPDFAnnotationFlagInvisible`][] flag will ignore annotation appearance streams.
- An annotation with a flag set to [`PSPDFAnnotationFlagHidden`][] wonâ€™t be displayed or printed.
- An annotation with a [`PSPDFAnnotationFlagPrint`][] flag will be printed. [`PSPDFAnnotationFlagPrint`][] is the default flag.
- An annotation with a flag set to [`PSPDFAnnotationFlagNoView`][] will not be displayed onscreen, but printing might be allowed.
- Annotations with a [`PSPDFAnnotationFlagReadOnly`][] flag donâ€™t allow user interactions. The flag is ignored for [widget annotations][`pspdfwidgetannotation`].
- If you want to prevent your users from editing an annotation, you can set the [`PSPDFAnnotationFlagLocked`][] and [`PSPDFAnnotationFlagLockedContents`][] flags.

